# API & Server Code — nikah-web

> Source: `typescript-zod-tailwind-nextjs-cursorrules-prompt-.mdc`, `nextjs-typescript-cursorrules-prompt-file.mdc`, `javascript-typescript-code-quality-cursorrules-pro.mdc`.

## API Response Shape

All responses **must** follow the project's actual convention (see `app/api/rsvp/route.ts`, `app/api/wishes/route.ts`):

```ts
// Success (read or write)
{ ok: true, data?: T, ...fields }

// Success (idempotent acknowledgement, e.g. honeypot)
{ ok: true }

// Error
{ ok: false, error: string, fields?: Record<string, string> }
```

> **Note:** This deviates from the upstream awesome-cursorrules recipe (`{ success, data, error: { code, message, details? } }`). The codebase uses `{ ok, error, fields }` everywhere; do **not** invent a new shape for a single route — match the existing routes instead.

Never return raw exceptions, stacks, or un-typed JSON to the client.

## Status Codes (semantic)

| Code | Use |
|------|-----|
| 200 | OK (read) |
| 201 | Created (write that produces a resource) |
| 204 | No content (delete) |
| 400 | Bad request (malformed input) |
| 401 | Unauthorized (no/invalid auth) |
| 403 | Forbidden (authed but not allowed) |
| 404 | Not found |
| 409 | Conflict (duplicate, version mismatch) |
| 422 | Unprocessable entity (reserved — not used; Zod validation returns 400 in this codebase, see line below) |
| 429 | Rate limited |
| 500 | Server error (sanitized) |

## Validation

- **Zod** at the boundary of every route / Server Action that has a body or query params.
- On parse failure, return `400` with `{ ok: false, error: "validation", fields: { <path>: <message> } }` (see `rsvp/route.ts` for the canonical shape; do **not** invent a new 422/details variant).
- Derive static types: `type Input = z.infer<typeof schema>`.

```ts
// app/api/contact/route.ts — matches existing /api/rsvp pattern
import { NextResponse } from "next/server"
import { z } from "zod"

const ContactSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1).max(120),
  email: z.email(),
  message: z.string().min(10).max(2000),
})

export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const body = await req.json().catch(() => null)
  const parsed = ContactSchema.safeParse(body)
  if (!parsed.success) {
    const fields: Record<string, string> = {}
    for (const issue of parsed.error.issues) {
      const key = issue.path.join(".") || "_"
      if (!fields[key]) fields[key] = issue.message
    }
    return NextResponse.json(
      { ok: false, error: "validation", fields },
      { status: 400 },
    )
  }
  // ... business logic ...
  return NextResponse.json({ ok: true }, { status: 201 })
}
```

## Errors

- **Aspirational:** Custom error classes (`AppError`, `ValidationError`, `NotFoundError`, `UnauthorizedError`, `ConflictError`, `RateLimitError`). **Not yet adopted in this codebase** — current routes use plain `NextResponse.json({ ok: false, error: "..." })`. Do not introduce these classes in a single route; if you add one, add it across the affected surface and update the rule.
- Top-level `try/catch` in every route handler / Server Action that has an `await` (the existing `rsvp` and `wishes` routes do this).
- **Never expose raw DB / third-party error messages** to the client. Log full detail server-side, return a sanitized message.
- When logging context, include at least `{ route, method }` and any safe request identifier (e.g. IP from `getClientIp`). `userId` and `durationMs` are encouraged but not required for public anonymous routes.

## Layered Architecture (server code)

- `route.ts` / `actions.ts` — controller: parse, validate, delegate. **No business logic.**
- `lib/server/services/*.service.ts` — service: business rules.
- `lib/server/repositories/*.repository.ts` — repository: DB / external IO only.
- Never call the DB outside a repository.
- Never call an external API directly from a route handler — wrap in a service or client module.

## Rate Limiting

- Apply to every **public** route (no `req.auth` / no session cookie) **that has a request body, query parameters, or other user input**. Read-only, side-effect-free, no-input routes (e.g. a `GET /api/health` liveness probe) are exempt by industry convention and need not be rate-limited. This aligns with `security.mdc`'s "accepts user input" scope.
- Use Upstash Ratelimit or equivalent; document the limit per route in a comment near the middleware.

## Auth

- Auth check happens in **middleware** (or at the very top of the route handler) — never buried in business logic.
- Fail closed: any uncertainty → 401.

## Secrets

- Read from `process.env` only. Validate with Zod at boot.
- Never log secrets, tokens, passwords, or PII.
- Never return a secret (even partially) in an API response.

## Logging

- **Current state:** the codebase uses `console.log` / `console.error` directly. There is no `lib/log.ts` yet.
- **Aspirational:** Structured JSON logs in production via `lib/log.ts` (pino / winston / Next's built-in). When introducing the logger, replace all `console.*` in a single PR — do not migrate one route at a time.
- Until the logger exists, prefer `console.log` / `console.error` with **structured payloads** (`JSON.stringify({ route, method, requestId, reason })`) so a future log shipper can parse them. Plain `console.log("something happened")` is still discouraged.
- Log levels: `debug` (dev only), `info`, `warn`, `error`.
